THE STRIKE APPARENTLY AFFECTED THE TEMPERATURE TRANSDUCER CONNECTED TO THE RTU  A TOP THE METER, CAUSING AN ERROR IN CALCULATIONS OF VOLUMES THROUGH THE STATION.  GAS MEASUREMENT SPECIALIST FOUND AN ALARM REFLECTING A LOW GAS TEMPERATURE. THE RTU WAS READING - 57.14 DEGREES F. THIS -57.14 DEGREE READING WAS 97 DEGREES F. LOWER THAN THE NORMAL TEMPERATURE OF THE GAS IN THE STATION,  WHICH IS NORMALLY 40 DEGREES F. THE ALARM LOG HISTORY FIRST LOGGED THE ALARM ON.    REASON FOR HIGH PERCENT OF UNACCOUNTED FOR GAS:    BOAZ GAS BOARD            02/16/2007  P.O. BOX 594  BOAZ, AL 35957  ON APPROXIMATELY AUGUST 18TH, 2005 A SERIES OF STRONG STORMS MOVED THROUGH OUR SERVICE AREA AND IT APPEARS A LIGHTNING STRIKE HIT OUR LEETH GAP GATE STATION.  THE STRIKE APPARENTLY AFFECTED THE TEMPERATURE TRANSDUCER CONNECTED TO THE RTU WAS READING -57.14 DEGREES F. THIS - 57.14 DEGREE READING WAS 97 DEGREES F. LOWER THAN THE NORMAL TEMPERATURE OF THE GAS IN THE STATION, WHICH IS NORMALLY 40 DEGREES F. THE ALARM LOG HISTORY FIRST LOGGED THE ALARM ON 08/18/2005.    MR. JODY LANEY OF MARIECO. INC. VISITED THE SITE EARLY IN APRIL 2006 AND FOUND THE PROBLEM AND CORRECTED IT BY REPLACING THE TEMPERATURE PROBE; THE TEMPERATURE BEGAN READING APPROXIMATELY 40 DEGREES, WHICH HAS BEEN NORMAL FOR THIS STATION.  HIS DETERMINATION IS ""THE MOST LIKELY FAILURE OF THE TEMPERATURE PROBE APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY LIGHTENING""    RULE: EACH 5 DEGREE TEMPERATURE CHANGE EQUATES TO 1% IN GAS COMPRESSIBILITY CALCULATION.    IN THIS CASE, IF THE GAS WAS NORMALLY AT 40 DEGREES HOWEVER THE CALCULATION WAS USING-57.14 DEGREES THE ERROR IS APPROXIMATELY 97 DEGREES OR APPROXIMATELY 19.4% ERROR, FOR EACH MCF OF GAS PASSING THROUGH THE METER.    THUS, FOR EVERY 1,000 CUBIC FEET OF GAS SHOWN TO HAVE FLOWED THROUGH THE METER ONLY 806 CUBIC FEET WAS RECEIVED.  THE REMAINING 194 CUBIC FEET WAS LEFT IN THE TRANSPORT COMPANIES LINE AND CONSUMED BY THEM.  WE WERE THEN FORCED TO PURCHASE ADDITIONAL QUANTITIES OF GAS OF OFFSET THE VOLUMES BEING LEFT IN THE TRANSPORTERS LINE.    THUS, FOR THIS REPORTING PERIOD THE HIGH PERCENTAGE OF UNACCOUNTED GAS OF 10% IS EXPLAINED DUE TO THE AFOREMENTIONED SITUATION.  DAYS IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING REPLACEMENT OF THE TEMPERATURE PROBE ALL PURCHASES AND SALES HAVE RE-ALIGNED AND APPEAR TO BE CORRECTED.    CRAIG RIGSBY, GENERAL MANAGER"	CRAIG RIGSBY	BOAZGAS@BELLSOUTH.NET	2565937362	2565936764
